EZEK_CONTEXT = {
  "1": {
    "1": "<p>Ezekiel was a priest who was deported to Babylon in the first deportation (597 BCE) and received his call-vision in 593 BCE by the Chebar canal in Babylonia ('the thirtieth year', 1:1 — possibly his own thirtieth year, the age for priestly service). He prophesied to the exilic community ca. 593-571 BCE. His priestly background shapes his theology: the book is preoccupied with divine glory (<em>kavod</em>), the departure of the Shekinah from the temple (chs. 8-11), and its eschatological return (chs. 40-48). The merkabah vision (ch. 1) was the most influential single vision in subsequent Jewish mysticism — the Hekhalot literature built an entire tradition of heavenly ascent around it. The four living creatures (lion, ox, eagle, human) reappear in Irenaeus's identification of the four Gospel symbols.</p>"
  },
  "37": {
    "1": "<p>The valley of dry bones vision (37:1-14) is addressed to the exilic community that had concluded 'our bones are dried up, our hope is lost, we are indeed cut off' (v. 11). The corporate resurrection metaphor — national restoration envisioned as bodily resurrection — uses the imagery of physical resurrection for Israel's return from exile. This is not a straightforward prophecy of individual eschatological resurrection (though the same imagery is applied there in Isa 26:19; Dan 12:2), but a bold use of resurrection as the metaphor for what only divine creative power could accomplish for the exiled nation. The NT develops the resurrection-from-exile typology: Christ's resurrection is both personal and the beginning of the great return-from-death that Ezekiel envisioned.</p>"
  }
}

EZEK_CHRIST = {
  "1": {
    "1": "<p>A pattern: &ldquo;The heavens opened and I saw divine visions.&rdquo; The opened heavens at Ezekiel&rsquo;s commission anticipate the opened heavens at Jesus&rsquo;s baptism (Matt 3:16: &ldquo;the heavens were opened&rdquo;) and at Stephen&rsquo;s martyrdom (Acts 7:56). When the eternal God addresses his prophets and his Son, the boundary between heaven and earth breaks open. Ezekiel&rsquo;s vision is the OT prototype of the Christophanic openings: in both cases a figure emerges from heaven to commission a messenger for a resistant audience.</p>",
    "2": "<p>A structural note: The parenthetical date formula confirms the historical anchor of the vision — the fifth year of Jehoiachin&rsquo;s exile (593 BCE). Ezekiel&rsquo;s ministry occurs in the context of exile and displacement, the same conditions into which the Son of God was born (&ldquo;no place to lay his head,&rdquo; Luke 9:58) and in which the church ministers until the consummation.</p>",
    "3": "<p>A pattern: &ldquo;The word of the LORD came to Ezekiel the priest.&rdquo; Ezekiel is a priest who becomes a prophet — the combining of the priestly and prophetic offices in one person is the OT anticipation of the one Mediator who is both great High Priest and the Word of God (Heb 4:14; John 1:1). The hand of YHWH upon him (the prophetic commissioning formula) is the precursor to the Spirit&rsquo;s descending on Jesus at his anointing (Luke 4:18).</p>",
    "4": "<p>A pattern: The theophanic storm from the north — whirlwind, cloud, fire, and gleaming metal — is the OT vocabulary for divine self-revelation in awesome power. This storm theophany pattern (found also in Job 38:1 and Ps 50:3) points forward to Christ&rsquo;s parousia described in the same register: lightning from east to west (Matt 24:27), angels with great power (Matt 24:31), the Son of Man coming in the clouds (Mark 13:26). The storm is how God appears when he comes to judge and redeem the earth.</p>",
    "5": "<p>A type: &ldquo;From the center of the fire came what looked like four living creatures.&rdquo; The four creatures that emerge from the divine fire reappear in Rev 4:6-8 surrounding the throne of God and the Lamb. John of Patmos identifies them as the same creatures Ezekiel saw, and their ceaseless worship (&ldquo;Holy, holy, holy, Lord God Almighty&rdquo;) is now addressed to the enthroned Christ. The creatures that bore YHWH&rsquo;s throne in Ezekiel&rsquo;s vision bear the throne in the new creation — connecting the divine presence in both testaments.</p>",
    "6": "<p>A structural type: The four faces of each creature (human, lion, ox, eagle) are the fourfold symbol of created life at its highest expression. The church fathers, particularly Irenaeus, identified these four faces with the four Gospels: Matthew (human, the Son of Man&rsquo;s genealogy), Mark (lion, opening roar of John the Baptist in the wilderness), Luke (ox, the sacrificial opening with Zechariah&rsquo;s priestly ministry), John (eagle, soaring theological vision). Whether or not this precise correspondence holds, the fourfold witness to Christ is embedded in the structure of the divine throne-vision.</p>",
    "7": "<p>A structural type: The straight legs and bronze hooves of the creatures suggest purposeful, irresistible movement — they travel wherever the Spirit directs without obstruction. The risen Christ&rsquo;s feet are described as &ldquo;like refined bronze&rdquo; in Rev 1:15 — the same material imagery Ezekiel uses. The bodily posture of the creatures suggests that divine purposes move forward with invincible precision; the same irresistibility characterizes the advance of Christ&rsquo;s kingdom.</p>",
    "8": "<p>A structural type: Human hands under the wings of the creatures represent the combination of transcendence (wings for heavenly movement) and agency (hands for earthly action). The Son of God assumes this combination in the incarnation: in Christ, transcendent divine power acts through human hands that heal, touch, and are pierced.</p>",
    "9": "<p>A structural note: The creatures move straight ahead without turning — wherever the Spirit directs, they go. This total responsiveness to the Spirit&rsquo;s direction is the prototype of Christ&rsquo;s own Spirit-directed ministry: he went precisely where the Father sent him, did nothing of his own initiative (John 5:19), and set his face like flint toward Jerusalem (Luke 9:51; Isa 50:7).</p>",
    "10": "<p>A type: The four faces (human, lion, ox, eagle) represent the fullness of created being in the presence of the Creator. In Christ, the fullness of divinity dwells bodily (Col 2:9) — he is the one in whom all four faces are unified: fully human, kingly like the lion (Rev 5:5), sacrificial like the ox (Heb 9:12), and soaring in divine omniscience like the eagle (John 1:48). The four-faced creatures anticipate the one who recapitulates all creation in himself.</p>",
    "11": "<p>A structural type: The wings spread outward and touching neighbors, with two covering the body — the double function of wings (active flight and protective covering) is reflected in Christ&rsquo;s gathering of his people: &ldquo;how often I wanted to gather your children together, as a hen gathers her chicks under her wings&rdquo; (Matt 23:37). The creatures&rsquo; covering wings are the OT type of the protecting, gathering wings of Christ.</p>",
    "12": "<p>A pattern: &ldquo;Each moved straight ahead — wherever the spirit directed them to go, they went.&rdquo; The absolute alignment between the Spirit&rsquo;s will and the creatures&rsquo; movement models the trinitarian coordination in redemption. Jesus declares: &ldquo;I can do nothing on my own... I seek not my own will but the will of him who sent me&rdquo; (John 5:30). The merkabah creatures model the Spirit-directed obedience that Christ himself embodies perfectly.</p>",
    "13": "<p>A type: Fire moving back and forth among the creatures, blazing like coals, with lightning flashing — this is the fire of the divine presence that never goes out. The same fire that purged Isaiah&rsquo;s lips (Isa 6:6-7) and descended at Pentecost (Acts 2:3-4) is the fire of divine holiness. Christ baptizes with the Holy Spirit and fire (Matt 3:11) — he is the one who distributes the divine fire throughout the world&rsquo;s communities.</p>",
    "14": "<p>A structural note: The creatures moved with the speed of lightning — instantaneous, incalculable speed of movement. The Son of Man coming at the last day is similarly described in terms of the instantaneous (Matt 24:27: &ldquo;as lightning flashes from the east to the west, so will be the coming of the Son of Man&rdquo;). The creatures&rsquo; lightning speed is the prototype of the eschatological event that cannot be anticipated by ordinary time.</p>",
    "15": "<p>A type: The four wheels (<em>ofannim</em>) beside each creature — one wheel per creature — integrate earthly mobility with heavenly direction. The wheel is associated in Ezekiel with the providential movement of YHWH&rsquo;s purposes through earthly history. In Christ, the eternal intersects with the historical: the Word became flesh (John 1:14) — the eternal wheel of divine purpose touched the earth at Bethlehem and rolled through history to the cross and resurrection.</p>",
    "16": "<p>A structural note: The wheels gleaming like beryl (topaz) with a wheel intersecting a wheel — the double-wheel structure allows movement in any direction without turning. The divine purposes in Christ cannot be trapped in a single historical trajectory: they move in every direction simultaneously (Eph 3:10: the manifold wisdom of God made known through the church) from the cross as its center point.</p>",
    "17": "<p>A structural note: The wheels could go in any of the four directions without turning — omnidirectional movement. The advance of the gospel into all nations and cultures without becoming &ldquo;foreign&rdquo; to any of them reflects this omnidirectionality: Christ is accessible from every direction (Rev 5:9: &ldquo;you were slain and purchased people for God from every tribe and language and people and nation&rdquo;) without requiring any group to turn away from their particular history.</p>",
    "18": "<p>A type: &ldquo;Their rims were high and awe-inspiring, and the rims of all four were covered with eyes all around.&rdquo; The eyes covering the wheel-rims are the omniscience of the divine chariot — it sees in every direction, nothing escapes its perception. Christ is described in Rev 1:14 with &ldquo;eyes like a flame of fire&rdquo; and in Rev 5:6 the Lamb has &ldquo;seven eyes, which are the seven spirits of God sent out into all the earth&rdquo; — omniscient awareness that penetrates the cosmos. The wheels&rsquo; eyes are the OT type of Christ&rsquo;s all-seeing, all-knowing presence.</p>",
    "19": "<p>A structural note: The synchronized movement of creatures and wheels — the creatures move, the wheels move; the creatures rise, the wheels rise — represents the perfect integration of heavenly direction and earthly execution. Christ&rsquo;s ministry exhibits the same integration: every movement of the Son is the Father&rsquo;s movement in him (&ldquo;the Father who dwells in me does his works,&rdquo; John 14:10).</p>",
    "20": "<p>A structural note: &ldquo;For the spirit of the living creature was in the wheels.&rdquo; The Spirit&rsquo;s indwelling of the wheels explains their synchrony with the creatures. The same principle governs the Spirit&rsquo;s work in Christ&rsquo;s body (the church): the Spirit in the community enables the body to move in alignment with the head (Eph 4:4-16). The merkabah&rsquo;s creature-wheel synchrony is the OT image of Spirit-body coherence.</p>",
    "21": "<p>A structural note: The creatures and wheels stop and move together in perfect coordination. The stillness of the cross — the moment when Christ was apparently stopped, immobilized on the cross — was precisely the moment of the Spirit&rsquo;s deepest work, achieving what no movement could: the atonement. The stopping of the divine chariot at Golgotha was its most decisive act.</p>",
    "22": "<p>A type: &ldquo;Spread out above the heads of the creatures was the likeness of a firmament, gleaming like crystal, awesome in its appearance.&rdquo; The crystal firmament separating the creatures from the throne above them anticipates the torn veil of the temple (Mark 15:38) — the boundary between the creaturely and the holy was impenetrable until Christ opened it. At the ascension, the risen Christ passes through this boundary permanently as the forerunner (Heb 6:20), establishing permanent access through himself for all who are in him.</p>",
    "23": "<p>A structural note: The creatures&rsquo; wings under the firmament — spread straight, touching — create a vast canopy of creaturely worship below the divine throne. This posture of spread wings in reverence before the divine presence is the posture of all creation before the Creator. In Christ, the creator entered below the firmament, into creaturely space, so that creatures might ascend into divine space through him.</p>",
    "24": "<p>A type: &ldquo;The sound of their wings like the roar of many waters, like the voice of the Almighty, a great rumbling like the noise of an army.&rdquo; The sound of many waters is the signature of the divine voice in both Ezekiel and Revelation. Christ&rsquo;s voice in Rev 1:15 is &ldquo;like the sound of many waters&rdquo; — the same sound Ezekiel hears from the creatures&rsquo; wings is the voice of the exalted Christ. The sound of the divine approach that overwhelmed Ezekiel is the sound of the risen Christ speaking to his church.</p>",
    "25": "<p>A structural note: &ldquo;A voice came from above the firmament over their heads. When they stood still, they lowered their wings.&rdquo; The creatures&rsquo; stillness and wing-lowering at the sound of the divine voice is the posture of all creation when Christ speaks. At Gethsemane, the Roman soldiers fell to the ground at Jesus&rsquo;s &ldquo;I am he&rdquo; (John 18:6) — a human echo of the creatures&rsquo; prostration before the divine voice.</p>",
    "26": "<p>A direct revelation: &ldquo;Above the likeness of the throne was a form with a human appearance.&rdquo; The human figure on the divine throne is the pre-incarnate Christ — YHWH in human form above the sapphire throne. Daniel sees the same figure: the Ancient of Days with the Son of Man approaching (Dan 7:9-14). The revelation is climactic: the God who appears on the throne has a human form, anticipating the incarnation where the one who has always had human-form on the throne becomes human in history. The throne&rsquo;s human-shaped occupant is identified in Revelation as the risen Jesus (Rev 4:2-3; 22:1, 3).</p>",
    "27": "<p>A direct revelation: &ldquo;From what appeared to be his waist upward I saw something like gleaming metal — fire enclosed all around.&rdquo; The fiery, radiant figure of YHWH on the throne is described in language that Revelation applies directly to the risen Christ: &ldquo;his face was like the sun shining in full strength&rdquo; (Rev 1:16); &ldquo;his feet were like refined bronze, refined in a furnace&rdquo; (Rev 1:15). John&rsquo;s inaugural vision of the exalted Christ in Rev 1:13-16 is a deliberate reworking of Ezekiel&rsquo;s throne-vision, identifying the risen Jesus as the fiery, radiant figure Ezekiel saw above the chariot-throne.</p>",
    "28": "<p>A direct revelation: &ldquo;Like the rainbow that appears in the clouds on a rainy day, so was the radiance that surrounded him. Such was the appearance of the likeness of the glory of the LORD.&rdquo; The rainbow around the divine glory connects the Noahic covenant promise (Gen 9:13-17: the rainbow as the sign that YHWH will never again destroy the earth by flood) with the divine presence. In Rev 4:3, the rainbow &ldquo;like an emerald&rdquo; surrounds the throne — indicating that the covenant faithfulness symbolized in the rainbow is the permanent attribute of the one on the throne. Ezekiel falls prostrate before the glory; in John 1:14, this glory dwells in Jesus Christ and the disciples &ldquo;beheld his glory.&rdquo;</p>"
  },
  "2": {
    "1": "<p>A type: &ldquo;Son of man, stand on your feet, and I will speak with you.&rdquo; The divine command to stand after prostration is a resurrection pattern: the prophet who falls before the divine glory is raised to stand and receive mission. Christ himself falls prostrate in Gethsemane (&ldquo;he fell on his face,&rdquo; Matt 26:39) and rises from death to stand as the exalted Lord. The &ldquo;son of man&rdquo; address — used 93 times in Ezekiel — is the title Jesus adopts for himself, linking his self-understanding to Ezekiel&rsquo;s commissioned humanity standing before the divine presence.</p>",
    "2": "<p>A type: &ldquo;As he spoke to me, the Spirit entered into me and set me on my feet.&rdquo; The Spirit&rsquo;s entry enabling the prophet to stand is the prophetic pattern of Spirit-empowered mission. Jesus is described as Spirit-empowered throughout his ministry (Luke 4:1, 14, 18), and the resurrection itself is attributed to the Spirit (&ldquo;the Spirit of him who raised Jesus from the dead,&rdquo; Rom 8:11). The Spirit who sets Ezekiel on his feet is the same Spirit who raises Christ from the dead and sets the church on its feet for mission (Acts 1:8).</p>",
    "3": "<p>A pattern: &ldquo;I am sending you to the Israelites — to nations that have rebelled against me.&rdquo; The prophetic commission to rebellious Israel is the OT pattern of Jesus&rsquo;s own mission: &ldquo;I was sent only to the lost sheep of the house of Israel&rdquo; (Matt 15:24); &ldquo;he came to his own, and his own people did not receive him&rdquo; (John 1:11). Ezekiel&rsquo;s commission to a persistently rebellious audience defines the prophetic task that Jesus takes on in his full scope — sent to the most resistant recipients.</p>",
    "4": "<p>A pattern: &ldquo;They are brazen-faced and stubborn-hearted... you shall say: Thus says the Lord GOD.&rdquo; The prophetic word is commanded regardless of the audience&rsquo;s condition. Jesus in John&rsquo;s Gospel speaks his words whether they are received or rejected: &ldquo;the words that I have spoken to you are spirit and life&rdquo; (John 6:63), yet many of his disciples turned back. The pattern of proclamation over resistance connects Ezekiel&rsquo;s commission to Jesus&rsquo;s ministry and then to the apostolic mission pattern of Acts.</p>",
    "5": "<p>A pattern: &ldquo;Whether they listen or refuse — for they are a rebellious house — they will know that a prophet has been among them.&rdquo; The ultimate vindication of the prophet&rsquo;s words comes through historical fulfillment rather than immediate reception. Jesus&rsquo;s prediction of Jerusalem&rsquo;s fall (Luke 21:20-24) was fulfilled in 70 CE, demonstrating after the fact that a prophet had been among them. The rejected word of Christ is eventually recognized even by those who rejected it — at the final judgment or in the retrospective of history.</p>",
    "6": "<p>A pattern: &ldquo;Do not be afraid of them, or be terrified by their looks, though they are a rebellious house.&rdquo; The anti-fear commission is given to Ezekiel because prophetic mission faces genuine hostility. Jesus commissions his disciples with similar anti-fear language (&ldquo;do not fear those who kill the body,&rdquo; Matt 10:28) and models it himself — he did not recoil from his opponents&rsquo; &ldquo;looks&rdquo; even when they picked up stones to throw at him (John 10:31-39).</p>",
    "7": "<p>A pattern: &ldquo;You shall speak my words to them, whether they listen or not.&rdquo; The unconditional quality of the prophetic commission — outcome-independent fidelity to the message — is the pattern of Jesus&rsquo;s own ministry and the apostolic mission. Paul echoes this in 2 Tim 4:2: &ldquo;preach the word; be ready in season and out of season.&rdquo; The prophet who speaks only when reception seems likely has already compromised the message.</p>",
    "8": "<p>A type: &ldquo;Do not be like that rebellious house. Open your mouth and eat what I give you.&rdquo; The eating of the divine word is the type of receiving God&rsquo;s revelation as nourishment. Jesus applies this to himself: &ldquo;I have food to eat that you do not know about... my food is to do the will of him who sent me&rdquo; (John 4:32-34). The divine word is not merely information to transmit but substance to be internalized — the prophet, like Christ, is consumed by the word before he speaks it.</p>",
    "9": "<p>A type: &ldquo;A hand stretched out toward me, and in it was a written scroll.&rdquo; The scroll given to Ezekiel by the divine hand is the OT archetype of the sealed scroll of Rev 5, which only the Lamb can open. The divine word comes to the prophet through the hand of YHWH — the same hand that, in the incarnation, stretched out on the cross. John the Apostle receives a similar scroll from the divine hand in Rev 10:8-10, consciously re-enacting Ezekiel&rsquo;s commissioning.</p>",
    "10": "<p>A type: &ldquo;He unrolled it before me — it had writing on both sides — and on it were lamentations, mourning, and woe.&rdquo; The scroll written on both sides filled with lament is the antithesis of the empty scroll — it is full of divine judgment against sin. The scroll of Rev 5 that only the Lamb can open is also described as written on the front and back (Rev 5:1), and when it is opened, it releases judgment into the world. Only Christ, having absorbed lamentations, mourning, and woe in his own person on the cross, has the right and capacity to open the scroll of divine judgment.</p>"
  },
  "3": {
    "1": "<p>A type: &ldquo;Son of man, eat what is before you — eat this scroll, then go and speak to the house of Israel.&rdquo; The command to eat the scroll before speaking is the prophetic-internalization type: the word must be received before it can be given. Jesus embodies this most fully: he is the Word who has always been the word, so there is no gap between reception and proclamation. &ldquo;The words that I speak to you I do not speak on my own authority, but the Father who dwells in me does his works&rdquo; (John 14:10) — Jesus speaks from infinite internalization of the Father&rsquo;s word.</p>",
    "2": "<p>A structural note: Ezekiel opens his mouth and receives the scroll. The obedient reception of the divine word — without question or delay — is the prototype of Jesus&rsquo;s immediate obedience to the Father&rsquo;s commission: &ldquo;the Son of Man came not to be served but to serve, and to give his life as a ransom for many&rdquo; (Mark 10:45). The opened mouth that receives the divine word is the posture of total readiness for the prophetic mission.</p>",
    "3": "<p>A type: &ldquo;In my mouth it was as sweet as honey.&rdquo; The word of lament sweet as honey in the prophet&rsquo;s mouth anticipates Ps 119:103 (&ldquo;how sweet are your words to my taste, sweeter than honey to my mouth&rdquo;) and Rev 10:9-10, where the angel gives John a scroll that is &ldquo;sweet as honey in my mouth, but when I had eaten it my stomach became bitter.&rdquo; Christ himself is described as the one in whom all divine wisdom and knowledge are hidden (Col 2:3) — consuming his word is consuming the sweetness of divine truth, even when the content is judgment.</p>",
    "4": "<p>A structural note: &ldquo;Go to the house of Israel and deliver my words to them.&rdquo; The commission to deliver YHWH&rsquo;s words is fulfilled ultimately in Christ, who is the Word delivered to Israel. John 1:11 summarizes the entire pattern: &ldquo;he came to his own, and his own did not receive him.&rdquo; Every prophetic commission to Israel is a partial anticipation of the final and complete Word-giving in the incarnation.</p>",
    "5": "<p>A structural note: &ldquo;You are not being sent to a people of foreign speech and a difficult language, but to the house of Israel.&rdquo; The fact that Israel — who already possesses the covenant and YHWH&rsquo;s words — is harder to reach than foreigners would have been is the OT diagnosis of covenant privilege without transformation. Jesus makes the same point: &ldquo;many will come from east and west and recline at table with Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob in the kingdom of heaven, while the sons of the kingdom will be thrown into outer darkness&rdquo; (Matt 8:11-12).</p>",
    "6": "<p>A pattern: &ldquo;If I had sent you to them, they would have listened.&rdquo; The hypothetical Gentile receptiveness to YHWH&rsquo;s word — greater than Israel&rsquo;s actual resistance — prefigures Jesus&rsquo;s ironic comparisons: the Queen of the South came to hear Solomon, and Nineveh repented at Jonah&rsquo;s preaching, yet something greater than Solomon and Jonah is here (Matt 12:41-42). Covenant privilege becomes covenant accountability.</p>",
    "7": "<p>A pattern: &ldquo;The house of Israel will not listen to you, because they will not listen to me.&rdquo; The rejection of the prophet is the rejection of YHWH — the principle Jesus explicitly applies to himself: &ldquo;whoever hears you hears me, and whoever rejects you rejects me&rdquo; (Luke 10:16); &ldquo;if they hated me, they will also hate you&rdquo; (John 15:18). The chain of rejection — YHWH → prophet → apostle — means that Israel&rsquo;s consistent pattern of rejection reaches its climax in the rejection of the Son.</p>",
    "8": "<p>A type: &ldquo;I have made your face as hard as their faces, and your forehead as hard as their foreheads.&rdquo; The hardening of Ezekiel&rsquo;s face to match Israel&rsquo;s stubbornness is the prophetic preparation for sustained resistance. Isa 50:7 applies the same language to the Servant: &ldquo;I have set my face like a flint; I know I will not be put to shame.&rdquo; Luke 9:51 says Jesus &ldquo;set his face to go to Jerusalem,&rdquo; using the same set-face language. The prophet and the Servant both receive a divine hardening for the mission of bearing witness before the resistant.</p>",
    "9": "<p>A type: &ldquo;I have made your forehead like adamant, harder than flint.&rdquo; The adamantine forehead given to Ezekiel for his mission is the OT image of prophetic determination before opposition. Jesus&rsquo;s determination toward Jerusalem — proceeding despite knowing the cross awaits — is the ultimate fulfillment of this prophetic resolve. The forehead harder than flint becomes the face set toward the skull-place where the final prophetic word would be delivered.</p>",
    "10": "<p>A pattern: &ldquo;Son of man, take all my words into your heart and hear them with your ears.&rdquo; The command to internalize the divine word completely — heart and ears — precedes mission. Jesus as the incarnate Word has not merely internalized the Father&rsquo;s words but is the Father&rsquo;s Word; there is no distinction in his case between reception and being. The command to Ezekiel points to what is true of Christ by nature.</p>",
    "11": "<p>A pattern: &ldquo;Go to the exiles, to your own people. Speak to them and say, &ldquo;Thus says the Lord GOD&rdquo; — whether they listen or not.&rdquo; The mission to the exiles, Ezekiel&rsquo;s own displaced people, is a type of Christ&rsquo;s mission to humanity in its condition of exile from Eden and from the Father. The gospel is the word spoken in the condition of exile — in the far country — calling the scattered to return (Luke 15:11-24).</p>",
    "12": "<p>A type: &ldquo;Then the Spirit lifted me up, and behind me I heard a great rumbling sound: &lsquo;Blessed be the glory of the LORD from his place!&rsquo;&rdquo; The Spirit&rsquo;s lifting of the prophet and the liturgical acclamation of YHWH&rsquo;s glory anticipates the ascension: the Spirit lifts Jesus into the heavenly realm (Acts 1:9), and the angels&rsquo; acclamation of the ascended Christ echoes the creatures&rsquo; and wheels&rsquo; proclamation of divine glory. &ldquo;Worthy is the Lamb who was slain to receive power and wealth and wisdom and might and honor and glory and blessing&rdquo; (Rev 5:12).</p>",
    "13": "<p>A structural note: The great roar of the creatures&rsquo; wings and the wheels — the sound of the divine chariot in motion — is the sound of YHWH acting in history. Every divine action in history is the chariot-movement of the Spirit. The incarnation is the chariot&rsquo;s most dramatic earthward movement; the parousia will be its final and most thunderous.</p>",
    "14": "<p>A pattern: &ldquo;I went in bitterness and grief of spirit, with the hand of the LORD resting powerfully upon me.&rdquo; Ezekiel&rsquo;s grief over his mission to rebellious Israel is the prophetic pattern of Christ&rsquo;s sorrow over Jerusalem: &ldquo;O Jerusalem, Jerusalem... how often would I have gathered your children together as a hen gathers her brood under her wings, and you were not willing&rdquo; (Matt 23:37). The prophetic grief is not weakness but faithfulness — feeling the weight of the mission before the resistant.</p>",
    "15": "<p>A pattern: &ldquo;I sat where they sat and remained among them for seven days, overwhelmed.&rdquo; Ezekiel&rsquo;s seven-day silent solidarity with the exiles at Tel-abib — sitting where they sat, sharing their condition before speaking — is the prophetic pattern of incarnational identification. Christ did not speak to humanity from a distance but entered human conditions fully: born in poverty, living as a refugee, dying with criminals. The prophet who sits where the people sit anticipates the God who &ldquo;became flesh and dwelt among us&rdquo; (John 1:14).</p>",
    "16": "<p>A structural note: After the seven days of silent solidarity, the word of YHWH comes to Ezekiel. The seven-day waiting period reflects the creation week — after the period of formation comes the word of purpose. Jesus&rsquo;s thirty years of hidden life in Nazareth precede his public ministry: the word is not given until the time of preparation is complete.</p>",
    "17": "<p>A type: &ldquo;Son of man, I have made you a watchman for the house of Israel.&rdquo; The watchman commission is one of the OT&rsquo;s most powerful prophetic images — the person whose function is to warn the city of approaching danger, responsible for the blood of those who die for lack of warning. Christ is the ultimate watchman: his eschatological discourse (Mark 13) is the great watchman&rsquo;s cry, calling Israel and the world to watch for the approach of the day of the Lord. The exhortation &ldquo;watch and pray&rdquo; (Mark 14:38; Matt 25:13) is Christ exercising his watchman function.</p>",
    "18": "<p>A type: &ldquo;If I say to the wicked, &lsquo;You will certainly die,&rsquo; and you give no warning... that wicked person will die for his sin, but I will require their blood from you.&rdquo; The watchman&rsquo;s blood-accountability for failure to warn establishes the moral weight of prophetic silence. Jesus fulfills the watchman commission absolutely — he never failed to warn, never accommodated the powerful to avoid confrontation (Matt 23:1-36), and his blood shed on the cross discharges all the blood-accountability accumulated by every prophet who ever warned and was not heeded.</p>",
    "19": "<p>A structural note: The watchman who warns faithfully has saved himself even if the warned person dies. Christ&rsquo;s faithfulness in his prophetic mission is the ground of his vindication — even when his words were rejected and he was executed, he had discharged the prophetic commission completely. The resurrection vindicates the rejected watchman.</p>",
    "20": "<p>A type: &ldquo;If a righteous person turns from their righteousness and commits sin, and I place a stumbling block before them, they will die.&rdquo; The stumbling block (<em>michshol</em>) placed by YHWH before the apostate righteous person connects to Paul&rsquo;s use of the stumbling block image for Christ himself: &ldquo;Christ crucified, a stumbling block to Jews&rdquo; (1 Cor 1:23); &ldquo;a stone of stumbling and a rock of offense&rdquo; (1 Pet 2:8, citing Isa 8:14). Christ becomes the stumbling block that separates those who persist in apostasy from those who stumble onto repentance.</p>",
    "21": "<p>A structural note: The watchman who warns the righteous against sin — and is heeded — has saved the righteous person. Christ&rsquo;s warnings of judgment in the Gospels are preventive medicine for the covenant community: &ldquo;if your right eye causes you to sin, tear it out and throw it away&rdquo; (Matt 5:29). The drastic preventive warning is the watchman&rsquo;s mode of saving the city from the approaching army.</p>",
    "22": "<p>A type: &ldquo;The hand of the LORD came upon me there, and he said to me: Get up and go out to the valley, and I will speak with you there.&rdquo; YHWH summons Ezekiel to a second encounter outside the inhabited space — the valley. The valley encounter repeats the pattern of the initial call-vision: divine initiative, unexpected location, overwhelming presence. Jesus regularly withdraws to unpopulated spaces for encounters with the Father (Mark 1:35; Luke 6:12) — the prophetic pattern of meeting God outside the crowd.</p>",
    "23": "<p>A type: &ldquo;The glory of the LORD was standing there, just like the glory I had seen by the River Chebar, and I fell on my face.&rdquo; The standing glory of YHWH in the valley and Ezekiel&rsquo;s prostration anticipates the transfiguration (Matt 17:6: the disciples &ldquo;fell on their faces and were terrified&rdquo;) and John&rsquo;s prostration before the exalted Christ (Rev 1:17: &ldquo;I fell at his feet as though dead&rdquo;). The glory of YHWH that appears to Ezekiel is the same glory that shines from the face of Jesus Christ (2 Cor 4:6).</p>",
    "24": "<p>A structural note: &ldquo;The Spirit entered into me and set me on my feet. He spoke to me and said, &lsquo;Go into your house and shut yourself inside.&rsquo;&rdquo; The Spirit-empowered standing followed by an instruction of strategic withdrawal — go inside, wait — echoes Christ&rsquo;s pattern of withdrawal before major actions (before the feeding of the 5000, John 6:15; before the last supper, Luke 22:8-12). Divine strategy sometimes requires withdrawal before the next forward movement.</p>",
    "25": "<p>A structural note: &ldquo;Cords will be put on you, and you will be tied with them so you cannot go out among the people.&rdquo; Ezekiel&rsquo;s binding — prevented from free movement among the people — is the prophetic type of Christ&rsquo;s binding at his arrest (&ldquo;they bound him and led him to Pilate,&rdquo; Matt 27:2). In both cases, the binding is not defeat but the constraint through which the divine purpose is accomplished: Ezekiel&rsquo;s immobility makes him a sign; Christ&rsquo;s binding leads to the cross.</p>",
    "26": "<p>A type: &ldquo;I will make your tongue stick to the roof of your mouth, and you will be silent.&rdquo; Ezekiel&rsquo;s prophetic silencing — able to speak only when YHWH opens his mouth — is the extreme form of the prophet&rsquo;s total dependence on the divine word. Christ&rsquo;s silence before Pilate (&ldquo;he gave him no answer, not even to a single charge,&rdquo; Matt 27:14) is the voluntary fulfillment of the Servant&rsquo;s silence: &ldquo;like a sheep before its shearers is silent, so he did not open his mouth&rdquo; (Isa 53:7). Prophetic silence is the most powerful word when the time for speech is past.</p>",
    "27": "<p>A type: &ldquo;Whenever I speak to you, I will open your mouth, and you will say to them, &lsquo;Thus says the Lord GOD.&rsquo;&rdquo; The opened mouth of the prophet — the antithesis of his silencing — is the Spirit&rsquo;s gift of proclamation. At Pentecost, the disciples&rsquo; mouths are opened by the Spirit (Acts 2:4) and they begin to speak in languages they did not know — the ultimate fulfillment of YHWH opening the prophet&rsquo;s mouth. Christ promises his disciples a similar opening: &ldquo;for it is not you who speak, but the Spirit of your Father speaking through you&rdquo; (Matt 10:20).</p>"
  },
  "4": {
    "1": "<p>A type: &ldquo;Take a clay tile and place it before you, then inscribe on it the city — Jerusalem.&rdquo; The enacted prophecy of the siege tile is Ezekiel&rsquo;s most dramatic prophetic sign-act. The inscribed city under siege is a type of Christ&rsquo;s weeping over Jerusalem: &ldquo;O Jerusalem, Jerusalem... your enemies will set up a barricade around you&rdquo; (Luke 19:41-44). Both the prophet&rsquo;s tile and the Savior&rsquo;s tears represent the same approaching reality — the siege and fall of the city that killed the prophets.</p>",
    "2": "<p>A structural note: The full siege apparatus inscribed or enacted around the clay tile — siege wall, ramp, encampments, battering rams — enacts the comprehensive nature of coming judgment. The precision of the enumeration (four siege elements) mirrors the precision of Babylon&rsquo;s actual siege of Jerusalem in 588-586 BCE. Jesus&rsquo;s description of Jerusalem&rsquo;s siege in Luke 21:20-24 is equally precise: &ldquo;when you see Jerusalem surrounded by armies, know that its desolation has come near.&rdquo;</p>",
    "3": "<p>A type: &ldquo;Take an iron griddle and stand it upright as an iron wall between yourself and the city.&rdquo; The iron wall between Ezekiel and the siege-city represents YHWH&rsquo;s judgment standing between him and Jerusalem — the divine presence as an impassable barrier of wrath. The same imagery appears in Lam 3:44 (&ldquo;you have wrapped yourself with a cloud so that no prayer can pass through&rdquo;). Christ on the cross cries &ldquo;my God, my God, why have you forsaken me&rdquo; (Matt 27:46) — the iron wall of divine judgment between Father and Son in the moment of atonement.</p>",
    "4": "<p>A type: &ldquo;Lie on your left side and take up the iniquity of the house of Israel upon yourself.&rdquo; This is the most explicit substitutionary bearing of sin in Ezekiel — the prophet physically enacts the taking of communal iniquity upon his own body. The language and structure directly anticipate Isa 53:4-6 (&ldquo;he has borne our griefs and carried our sorrows... the chastisement of our peace was upon him&rdquo;). Christ&rsquo;s bearing of sin on the cross is the ultimate fulfillment of Ezekiel&rsquo;s enacted bearing: where Ezekiel bore it symbolically for days, Christ bore it actually and once for all.</p>",
    "5": "<p>A structural note: The 390 days representing the years of Israel&rsquo;s iniquity have been calculated in various ways by interpreters (some find 390 years from the division of the kingdom to the fall of Jerusalem; others calculate from earlier reference points). Regardless of the precise calculation, the correspondence of days to years establishes the principle that prophetic time is measured differently from calendar time — the temporal density of sin and judgment does not fit ordinary chronology. Paul&rsquo;s similar compaction of the &ldquo;fullness of time&rdquo; when Christ was born (Gal 4:4) reflects this prophetic-time sensibility.</p>",
    "6": "<p>A type: &ldquo;When those days are finished, roll onto your right side and bear the iniquity of the house of Judah: forty days, a day for each year.&rdquo; The 40 days of bearing Judah&rsquo;s iniquity connects to the OT&rsquo;s several 40-day/40-year periods of testing and preparation: the flood, the wilderness, Moses on Sinai. Jesus fasts 40 days in the wilderness before his ministry (Matt 4:2), bearing in his own person the wilderness testing that Israel failed. The 40-day pattern is the preparation-through-bearing that leads to mission.</p>",
    "7": "<p>A structural note: &ldquo;Turn your face toward the besieged Jerusalem with your arm bared, and prophesy against her.&rdquo; The bared arm (<em>zeroa choluf</em>) is the gesture of military action — YHWH acts against Jerusalem with his own arm. The same image appears in the exodus (&ldquo;by a mighty hand and an outstretched arm,&rdquo; Deut 26:8) but here reversed: the arm that delivered Israel from Egypt now acts in judgment against Israel. Christ&rsquo;s lament over Jerusalem (&ldquo;would that you had known the things that make for peace,&rdquo; Luke 19:42) is the fully personal counterpart of Ezekiel&rsquo;s directed prophecy.</p>",
    "8": "<p>A structural note: The cords binding Ezekiel to his side for the duration of the sign-act create a physical compulsion that mirrors the compulsion of the prophet&rsquo;s call. Jeremiah describes the same compulsion: &ldquo;if I say I will not speak any more in his name, then within me it is like a burning fire shut up in my bones, and I am weary of holding it back, and I cannot&rdquo; (Jer 20:9). Christ&rsquo;s willingness to be bound at Gethsemane (&ldquo;all this has taken place that the Scriptures might be fulfilled,&rdquo; Matt 26:56) is the ultimate acceptance of the binding that accomplishes the divine purpose.</p>",
    "9": "<p>A type: The multi-grain siege bread — wheat, barley, beans, lentils, millet, emmer — eaten during the siege-sign enacts the famine conditions of a besieged city. The mixing of five grains that would not normally be combined represents desperation and scarcity. Jesus feeds the 5,000 from five loaves (a different kind of five-grain provision) — not scarcity but superabundance; not the bread of judgment but the bread of grace. Christ is the bread of life that replaces the famine bread: &ldquo;whoever comes to me shall not hunger&rdquo; (John 6:35).</p>",
    "10": "<p>A structural note: The rationed food (twenty shekels by weight per day) and the measured water (one-sixth of a hin) establish the conditions of extreme scarcity that the besieged city will experience. In contrast, Christ at the wedding of Cana provides 120-180 gallons of wine (John 2:6) — superabundance where scarcity was expected. The contrast between Ezekiel&rsquo;s rationed bread and Christ&rsquo;s abundant provision is the contrast between judgment and grace.</p>",
    "11": "<p>A structural note: The measured water — a sixth of a hin drunk at set times — continues the rationing image. Isaiah&rsquo;s vision of eschatological blessing includes &ldquo;streams in the desert&rdquo; (Isa 35:6) and Ezekiel&rsquo;s own vision includes the rivers of living water flowing from the temple (Ezek 47). Christ promises &ldquo;rivers of living water will flow from within him&rdquo; (John 7:38) — the measured water of judgment is replaced by the overflowing water of life.</p>",
    "12": "<p>A type: The command to bake barley bread over human excrement — maximum ritual defilement — is one of the most extreme prophetic sign-acts in the OT. The defilement of the food supply represents the ultimate covenantal degradation: eating what is ritually impure under duress, because no other fuel is available. Christ &ldquo;became sin for us&rdquo; (2 Cor 5:21) — entering into the maximum degradation on behalf of those who had corrupted themselves. Where Ezekiel protests the defilement (v. 14), Christ accepted it voluntarily.</p>",
    "13": "<p>A structural note: &ldquo;This is how the Israelites will eat their defiled bread among the nations to which I drive them.&rdquo; The exile as defiled-bread eating among the nations is the condition from which Christ&rsquo;s redemption liberates: the Gentile mission (Acts 10-11) specifically overturns the clean/unclean food barriers as a sign that the exile-condition of defilement among the nations has been ended in Christ. Peter&rsquo;s vision of the unclean animals (Acts 10:15: &ldquo;what God has made clean, do not call common&rdquo;) is the direct reversal of Ezekiel&rsquo;s defiled-bread oracle.</p>",
    "14": "<p>A pattern: &ldquo;Ah, Lord GOD! I have never defiled myself.&rdquo; Ezekiel&rsquo;s priestly protest against eating defiled bread — his lifelong ritual purity — is the prophetic analog of Christ&rsquo;s sinlessness. Christ, the great High Priest, is &ldquo;holy, innocent, unstained, separated from sinners&rdquo; (Heb 7:26) — he had never defiled himself. Yet he accepted the defilement of sin imputed to him on the cross, just as Ezekiel was granted the concession of cattle dung rather than human excrement — but with Christ there is no concession, no substitute: he took the full defilement.</p>",
    "15": "<p>A structural note: YHWH&rsquo;s concession — cattle dung instead of human excrement — reflects the mercy that modifies but does not cancel judgment. Ezekiel&rsquo;s priestly integrity is accommodated within the sign-act. In Christ, there is no such moderation of the defilement accepted: he drank the cup of divine judgment to the dregs (Mark 14:36: &ldquo;remove this cup from me... yet not what I will, but what you will&rdquo;), where Ezekiel was permitted a lighter version of the symbol.</p>",
    "16": "<p>A type: &ldquo;Son of man, I am about to break the food supply in Jerusalem; they will eat their rationed bread with dread and drink their measured water with despair.&rdquo; The breaking of the food supply is the direct reversal of the covenant blessing (&ldquo;you shall eat your bread to the full, and I will give peace in your land,&rdquo; Lev 26:5). Christ at the Last Supper breaks bread and pours wine — reversing the broken/measured imagery: &ldquo;this is my body, broken for you... this cup is the new covenant in my blood&rdquo; (1 Cor 11:24-25). The bread and wine of blessing replace the rationed bread and water of judgment.</p>",
    "17": "<p>A structural note: &ldquo;They will lack bread and water, look at each other in horror, and waste away because of their iniquity.&rdquo; The wasting away of covenant breakers — not from famine alone but from the moral horror of recognizing what their iniquity has produced — is the condition from which Christ&rsquo;s gospel delivers. The prodigal son &ldquo;was perishing with hunger&rdquo; in the far country (Luke 15:17) and &ldquo;came to himself&rdquo; — the same recognition-of-iniquity moment that precedes return. Christ provides what satisfies the wasting — &ldquo;I am the bread of life; whoever comes to me shall not hunger&rdquo; (John 6:35).</p>"
  },
  "5": {
    "1": "<p>A type: &ldquo;Take a sharp sword and use it as a barber&rsquo;s razor — run it over your head and your beard.&rdquo; The use of a sword as a razor is the deliberately violent sign: military destruction functions as a barber&rsquo;s tool. The shaving of the head is a sign of extreme mourning (Job 1:20) and priestly defilement (Lev 21:5 — priests must not shave their heads). Ezekiel the priest is commanded to perform an act of priestly self-desecration as a prophetic sign. Christ, the ultimate High Priest, undergoes the extreme degradation of the crown of thorns (Matt 27:29) — the thorns of the curse (Gen 3:18) pressed into the head of the priest who bears the people&rsquo;s iniquity.</p>",
    "2": "<p>A type: The three-part division of the hair — a third burned in the city, a third cut with a sword, a third scattered to the wind — is the judgment threefold: pestilence and famine, sword, and dispersion. The number three as a judgment structure anticipates the three-fold description of the trumpets and bowls in Revelation, where a third of creation is afflicted in each wave. Christ&rsquo;s three-day death and burial is the absorbing of judgment into himself before the third-day resurrection reverses the pattern.</p>",
    "3": "<p>A structural note: &ldquo;Take a small number of the hairs and tuck them into the folds of your cloak.&rdquo; The small remnant preserved within the prophet&rsquo;s cloak is the preserved remnant of Israel — a small number secured against the totality of judgment. The cloak-remnant is the OT type of the remnant preserved by grace (Rom 11:5: &ldquo;at the present time there is a remnant chosen by grace&rdquo;). Christ is the cloak in which the remnant is preserved — hidden in him, they are kept through the judgments that sweep away the majority.</p>",
    "4": "<p>A structural note: &ldquo;Take some of those very hairs and throw them into the fire to burn; from that fire a flame will spread to all the house of Israel.&rdquo; Even the remnant does not escape judgment entirely — fire spreads from the cloak-hairs to all Israel. The purifying fire that touches even the preserved remnant is the refiner&rsquo;s fire of Mal 3:2-3: &ldquo;who can stand when he appears? For he is like a refiner&rsquo;s fire... he will refine them like gold and silver.&rdquo; Christ&rsquo;s own death is the fire that purifies the remnant, not merely the judgment that destroys the rebellious.</p>",
    "5": "<p>A direct revelation: &ldquo;This is Jerusalem — I placed her in the center of the nations, with countries surrounding her on all sides.&rdquo; Jerusalem&rsquo;s position at the center of the nations is the theological geography of the OT: the covenant city is the hub of the world&rsquo;s moral order. The Christ-event is described in Galatians as occurring &ldquo;in the fullness of time&rdquo; (Gal 4:4) — at the center-point of human history. Jerusalem&rsquo;s geographic centrality becomes the historical centrality of the cross: the redemption accomplished at the center of the nations radiates outward to the ends of the earth (Acts 1:8: Jerusalem, Judea, Samaria, the ends of the earth).</p>",
    "6": "<p>A structural note: &ldquo;She has turned against my laws more than the nations, and defied my statutes more than the surrounding countries.&rdquo; Jerusalem&rsquo;s sin is worse than the nations&rsquo; because it is covenant violation — the greater the privilege, the greater the accountability. Jesus makes the same indictment: &ldquo;the men of Nineveh will rise at the judgment with this generation and condemn it, for they repented at the preaching of Jonah, and something greater than Jonah is here&rdquo; (Matt 12:41). Covenant privilege without covenant faithfulness produces the greatest condemnation.</p>",
    "7": "<p>A structural note: &ldquo;Because you have exceeded the nations around you in rebellion.&rdquo; The comparative judgment — not merely sinning but exceeding the surrounding nations in sin — echoes the logic of Amos 1-2, where Israel&rsquo;s judgment is the climax of judgments on the surrounding nations. Jesus&rsquo;s judgment on Capernaum is similarly comparative: &ldquo;if the mighty works done in you had been done in Sodom, it would have remained until this day. But I tell you that it will be more tolerable on the day of judgment for the land of Sodom than for you&rdquo; (Matt 11:23-24).</p>",
    "8": "<p>A direct revelation: &ldquo;I — yes, I myself — am against you, and I will carry out my judgments against you in the full sight of the nations.&rdquo; The repeated first-person emphasis (<em>gam ani</em>, I myself) makes YHWH the judge of his own covenant people in the presence of the nations. The cross is the ultimate judgment carried out in full sight: Christ, bearing the judgment of the covenant people, dies publicly, before the assembled representatives of the nations (Jews from every nation, Acts 2:5; Roman soldiers; Gentile authorities). The judgment in full sight of the nations is fulfilled in the crucifixion.</p>",
    "9": "<p>A structural note: &ldquo;I will do to you what I have never done before, and what I will never do again, on account of all your abominations.&rdquo; The unprecedented quality of YHWH&rsquo;s judgment on Jerusalem has a corresponding unprecedented quality in Christ&rsquo;s atonement: the cross is the once-for-all sacrifice (Heb 9:26: &ldquo;he has appeared once for all at the end of the ages to put away sin by the sacrifice of himself&rdquo;). The unique, unrepeatable character of the judgment on Jerusalem finds its redemptive counterpart in the unique, unrepeatable sacrifice of the Son of God.</p>",
    "10": "<p>A structural note: &ldquo;Fathers will eat their sons within you, and sons will eat their fathers.&rdquo; The cannibalism of extreme famine — the ultimate inversion of family and human order — is the covenant curse of Lev 26:29 and Deut 28:53-57, historically fulfilled in the sieges of 586 BCE (Lam 4:10) and 70 CE (Josephus, Jewish War). Christ weeps over the coming horror (Luke 19:41-44) rather than inflicting it with detachment — the judge of Jerusalem is also its mourner.</p>",
    "11": "<p>A direct revelation: &ldquo;Because you defiled my sanctuary with all your vile practices and abominations, I will cut you down; my eye will not spare and I will not show compassion.&rdquo; The defilement of the sanctuary triggers YHWH&rsquo;s full judicial withdrawal of mercy. The temple cleansings in the NT (John 2:13-22; Matt 21:12-13) are Jesus&rsquo;s prophetic declaration that the same defilement is happening in the Second Temple. Jesus&rsquo;s first cleansing citation — &ldquo;my house will be called a house of prayer, but you are making it a den of robbers&rdquo; — is precisely Ezekiel&rsquo;s complaint in priestly-judicial form.</p>",
    "12": "<p>A type: &ldquo;A third of you will die by plague and be consumed by famine within the city; a third will fall by the sword around you; and a third I will scatter to every wind.&rdquo; The threefold judgment — plague/famine, sword, scattering — is the complete dismantling of the covenant community. Christ&rsquo;s death absorbs all three modes of covenant judgment: he experiences plague-like desolation (&ldquo;my God, why have you forsaken me,&rdquo; citing Ps 22&rsquo;s plague imagery), dies by the sword of Roman execution, and his disciples scatter (&ldquo;you will all fall away,&rdquo; Mark 14:27, citing Zech 13:7). The shepherd absorbs what would otherwise scatter the flock.</p>",
    "13": "<p>A structural note: &ldquo;Then my anger will be exhausted, my fury will rest upon them and find its end... when I have spent my fury on them.&rdquo; The language of divine fury being &ldquo;spent&rdquo; and &ldquo;finding its end&rdquo; (<em>venachamti</em>, and I will be comforted/satisfied) is the OT theology of propitiation: YHWH&rsquo;s anger burns until it has fully accomplished judgment and is then satisfied. The cross is where YHWH&rsquo;s fury over sin is fully spent on Christ: the propitiation (Rom 3:25; 1 John 2:2) means that the divine fury finds its end in the person of the Son rather than in the destruction of his people.</p>",
    "14": "<p>A structural note: &ldquo;I will make you a ruin and a disgrace among the surrounding nations, in the sight of all who pass by.&rdquo; Jerusalem as a ruin passed by with horror — the covenant city becoming a warning to the nations — is the Lamentations motif (Lam 1:12: &ldquo;is it nothing to you, all you who pass by?&rdquo;). The same phrasing is applied by the mockers at the cross: &ldquo;those who passed by derided him, wagging their heads&rdquo; (Mark 15:29). Christ on the cross is the covenant city in miniature — the one who embodies Israel bearing her judgment, becoming a spectacle before passing nations.</p>",
    "15": "<p>A structural note: &ldquo;You will be a disgrace and a mockery, a warning and a horror, to the surrounding nations when I carry out my judgments against you in anger.&rdquo; The language of &ldquo;disgrace, mockery, warning, horror&rdquo; precisely describes Christ on the cross from the watching crowd&rsquo;s perspective: &ldquo;he saved others; let him save himself, if he is the Christ of God&rdquo; (Luke 23:35); &ldquo;if you are the King of the Jews, save yourself&rdquo; (Luke 23:37). The watching nations saw only the disgrace; the cross as warning and horror was transparent only to faith.</p>",
    "16": "<p>A structural note: &ldquo;When I launch against you the deadly arrows of famine aimed at destruction.&rdquo; The arrows of famine as divine weapons echo the bow-and-arrow imagery of divine judgment in Ps 38:2 and Lam 3:12-13. Christ at Gethsemane asks if the cup can pass from him (Matt 26:39) — the cup of divine judgment including famine, sword, plague. Having absorbed the arrows of divine wrath, he becomes the source of bread for the world: &ldquo;I am the bread of life; whoever comes to me shall not hunger&rdquo; (John 6:35).</p>",
    "17": "<p>A structural note: &ldquo;I will unleash famine, ferocious beasts, pestilence, bloodshed, and the sword upon you. I, the LORD, have spoken.&rdquo; The five-fold judgment (famine, beasts, pestilence, bloodshed, sword) echoes Ezek 14:21&rsquo;s four sore judgments and anticipates Rev 6&rsquo;s four horsemen. Christ&rsquo;s work reverses each: he provides bread (famine), is &ldquo;the Lion of the tribe of Judah&rdquo; (beast reversed), heals diseases (pestilence), shed no blood unjustly (bloodshed), and was himself pierced by the sword (John 19:34; Zech 13:7). The five-fold judgment absorbed by Christ becomes the ground of the five-fold blessing of the new covenant.</p>"
  },
  "34": {
    "11": "<p>A direct revelation: 'For thus says the Lord GOD: Behold I, I myself will search for my sheep and seek them out ... I will rescue them from all places where they have been scattered ... I will seek the lost and I will bring back the strayed and I will bind up the injured and I will strengthen the weak.' Jesus's 'I am the good shepherd' (John 10:11) and the parable of the lost sheep (Luke 15:4-6) are the incarnational enactment of Ezek 34's promise. What YHWH said he himself would do (in contrast to the failed shepherds of Israel's leaders) is what Jesus does: the divine shepherd-promise is fulfilled by the Son who is YHWH present in person, doing what YHWH promised he personally would do for the scattered flock.</p>"
  },
  "36": {
    "27": "<p>A direct revelation: 'And I will put my Spirit within you and cause you to walk in my statutes and be careful to obey my rules.' Pentecost is Ezekiel 36:27 enacted. The Spirit's indwelling is not merely motivational but causally efficacious: 'I will cause you to walk' — the Hebrew Hiphil form makes YHWH the enabling cause of the obedience that follows. This is the new covenant's answer to the old covenant's demand without the enabling Spirit: the same Torah-standard now fulfilled because the Spirit from within enables what the law from without could only command. Paul's 'the righteous requirement of the law might be fulfilled in us who walk not according to the flesh but according to the Spirit' (Rom 8:4) is the Christological-pneumatological fulfillment of Ezek 36:27.</p>"
  },
  "47": {
    "9": "<p>A type: 'And wherever the river goes, every living creature that swarms will live, and there will be very many fish. For this water goes there, that the waters of the sea may become fresh; so everything will live where the river goes.' The eschatological temple-river of Ezekiel's vision (ch. 47), increasingly deep and life-giving, is the OT type for the water that flows from Christ. Jesus at Tabernacles (John 7:38-39) applies the Spirit-water promise to himself: 'rivers of living water will flow from within him' — and John explains this is the Spirit. Revelation's new creation river (22:1) flowing from the throne of God and the Lamb completes the Ezekiel type: the new temple's river is Christ himself, and all who drink from him live.</p>"
  }
}

